Phenotypic synapomorphies are not known for this genus. Morphologically, Selvasaura gen. n. can be distinguished from all other genera of Cercosaurinae by the combination of the following characters: lower palpebral disc transparent, not divided (divided in Andinosaura , Euspondylus , Gelanesaurus , Oreosaurus , Petracola , Riama , and most Anadia and Placosoma species; opaque in Pholidobolus ); dorsal scales slightly rugose (smooth in Anadia ; keeled in Cercosaura ; strongly keeled and tuberculate in Echinosaura , Gelanesaurus , Neusticurus , Potamites ; minute tubercles on posterior dorsal scales in Placosoma ); lateral scales distinctly smaller than dorsal scales (lateral scales not distinctly reduced in size in Macropholidus ); lateral scales adjacent to ventrals non-granular (granular in Proctoporus ) (see e.g., Oftedal 1974 ; Cadle and Chuna 1995 ; Altamirano-Benavides et al. 2013 ; Kok et al. 2013 ; Torres-Carvajal and Mafla-Endara 2013 ;
Echevarria et al. 2015
; Borges-Nojosa et al. 2016 ;
Chavez et al. 2017
;
Sanchez-Pacheco et al. 2017b
). Genetically, the genus is differentiated from the other cercosaurines by distances given in Table 3 and 4.

